node.title: Most Covid Vaccines Will Work as Boosters, Study Suggests
node.description: In a comparison of seven different brands, researchers found that most shots give a strong boost, even in mix-and-match combinations.

node.title: Stolen School Bus Rams Cars in New York City, at Least 1 Officer and 1 Civilian Hurt
node.description: The suspected driver of the stolen school bus was taken into custody Thursday afternoon, authorities said.

node.title: Labor announces 2030 emissions reductions target
node.description: Federal Labor is committing to cutting greenhouse gas emissions by 43 per cent by 2030, if it wins government at the next election.

node.title: Squares, Blocks, Cubes — What Is Happening in Silicon Valley?
node.description: Twitter’s new boss needs to boost the company’s value, or someone else will.

node.title: Overdoses Have Skyrocketed During the Pandemic. How Do We Stop Them?
node.description: More than 100,000 Americans died of overdoses in a single year, exceeding the number of people who died from car crashes and guns combined.

node.title: BuzzFeed readies public stock offering amid worker protest.
node.description: BuzzFeed will make its market debut as soon as Monday. As shareholders voted on the deal, some of the media company’s employees staged a work stoppage.

node.title: Shell pulls out of a U.K. oil field targeted by climate activists.
node.description: The field, known as Cambo and seen as a bellwether for Britain’s North Sea energy industry, awaits a government decision before it can be developed.

node.title: Man Who Planted Razor Blades in Pizza Dough Gets 5 Years in Prison
node.description: No one was reported injured, but prosecutors say that the recall prompted by Nicholas Mitchell’s tampering resulted in nearly $230,000 in losses to a Maine-based supermarket chain.

node.title: How the Suburbs Have Changed Gerrymandering
node.description: Republicans have historically used the suburbs to defend against the electoral threat of cities. Now the suburbs themselves are posing the threat.

node.title: Angela Merkel’s Parting Message to Germany: Trust One Another
node.description: With a parade of torch-bearing soldiers and a 1970s hit from the Communist East, Germany’s Angela Merkel bid farewell as chancellor. She leaves office next week.

node.title: Adam Schiff Says House 'Averted' Shutdown, Vote Now Goes to Senate
node.description: The vote was passed along party lines, 221-212. Representative Adam Kinzinger was the only Republican to join the Democrats in voting "yes."

node.title: Jussie Smollett's Lawyer Says Judge Lunged at Her During Exchange Over Homophobic Slur
node.description: Lawyer Tamara Walker accused the presiding judge of "physically lunging" at her and asked for a mistrial. The judge denied her motion.

node.title: Nurse Charged With Creating Fake Vaccine Card for Relative With 'Anti-Vaccination Beliefs'
node.description: Tammy McDonald faces 15 years for allegedly forging a COVID-19 vaccination card and five years for lying to federal agents about it.

node.title: New Jersey GOP Lawmakers Briefly Blocked From Assembly After Failing to Show Vax Proof
node.description: The requirement to present vaccination proof or a negative test before entering the New Jersey Assembly chamber went into effect Thursday.

node.title: Man Who Put Razors, Screws in Pizza Dough Sentenced to Nearly 5 Years in Prison
node.description: The man was also ordered to pay almost $230,000 in restitution to Hannaford supermarkets, which carried and sold the tainted pizza dough.

node.title: Video Shows SUV Reportedly Involved in Hit-and-Run Crash Into Fountain
node.description: The car breaks through a barrier, and briefly travels through the air before crashing down and stopping in the fountain.

node.title: Experts Say Rise in U.S. Autism Cases Reflects More Awareness, Better Services
node.description: The analysis done by the CDC said in 2018 children who were 8-years-old were diagnosed with autism 1 in 44 times compared to 1 in 54 times during 2016.

node.title: Noticed the price of ginger lately? Growers ask why supermarkets mark up local ginger by 400 per cent
node.description: If you buy ginger from a major supermarket, you could be paying four times the price the farmer receives at the central markets, and Australian ginger growers want to know why.

node.title: Brothers Tried to Get Jussie Smollett to Pay Them $1M to Not Testify, Defense Lawyer Says
node.description: Smollett's defense attorneys allege the men carried out the attack on the actor, then tried to extort him for $1 million each after being questioned by police.

node.title: Nikki Haley to Be First Woman to Receive Replica Revolutionary War Musket From The Citadel
node.description: The award will be presented at the Patriot Dinner hosted by The Citadel Republican Society, which claims to be "the largest Republican club in the South."

node.title: No change to booster program after advice from ATAGI
node.description: The national expert vaccine group has recommended there be no widespread change to Australia's vaccine booster program, except for severely immunocompromised people, who can receive a booster shot two months after their second dose.

node.title: West Indies cricketing great wins top book award
node.description: The West Indies bowling great Michael Holding's book "Why We Kneel, How We Rise" has won the William Hill Sports Book of the Year award.

node.title: NZ to stay out of domestic politics in the Solomon Islands - Mahuta

node.title: NFL suspends Antonio Brown for misrepresenting vaccine status
node.description: Brown, his teammate Mike Edwards and free agent John Franklin III will each miss their next three games, the league said.
